Class Lass:<br><br>
&quot;When you joined the military and went to war had you<br>
given any thought to that process at all, or believe there was a historical way to deal with the returning Vietnam vets?&quot;<br><br>
Speaking for myself, I had no motivation to consider anything other than the honor and respect shown other returning vererans from prior conflicts, for which there was ample historical evidence. As far as returning was concerned, the only thing of consideration was not to return in a body bag. Under the age of 25, I don't think may have thoughts more sophisticated.<br><br>
&quot;What did you think that contract with society entailed? Was this the civilian or military society, or something or someone else.&quot;<br><br>
Aren't we getting a little academic crispy around the edges? The People of the United States sent us over there. The People of the United States had an obligation to effect closure. If it were not such a big thing, why were we sent in the first place? To drum up a reason to subject us to ridicule, just for fun?<br><br>
&quot;And...who was responsible for seeing this contract was fulfilled? If no one is designated responsible, whatever it is to be done probably won't ever happen.&quot;<br><br>
I don't think the real world in this situation operates on contractual law. Everyone in the country was responsible. As far as &quot;designees&quot; are concerned, I don't think we have ever had a corps of greeting cheerleaders. Did I miss something when I stepped off the plane? Were they like professional mourners?<br><br>
Am I missing something else, or are you beginning to sound like our old insensitive, detached, and outrageous friend Kali Tal?<br><br>
Art  
